---
// Homeowner Guide article: how to hire a painter in Brevard County after Florida's 2021 licensing change.
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = 'Hiring a Painter in Brevard County, FL | If Walls Could Talk';
const description =
  'What to look for when hiring a painter in Brevard County — insurance, written agreements, communication, and how to avoid the most common mistakes Florida homeowners make.';

const phone = '(321) 557-6959';
const phoneHref = 'tel:+13215576959';

const moreGuideLinks = [
  { label: 'Questions to Ask Before You Hire', href: '/homeowner-guide/questions-to-ask-before-you-hire' },
  { label: 'Understanding Paint Products in Florida', href: '/homeowner-guide/paint-products-florida' },
  { label: 'What to Expect During Your Project', href: '/homeowner-guide/what-to-expect-during-your-project' },
];
---

<Layout {title} {description}>
  <main class="page-container py-12 sm:py-16">
    <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-10 text-base leading-relaxed text-charcoal sm:space-y-12 sm:text-lg">
      <header class="space-y-4">
        <h1 class="font-display text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
          Hiring a Painter in Brevard County, FL
        </h1>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-muted">
          <p>
            Finding a painter in Brevard County is easy. Finding one who communicates well, does solid prep work,
            chooses the right materials for our Florida climate, and stands behind their work takes a little more
            effort.
          </p>
          <p>
            This page will help you know what actually matters when hiring a painter on the Space Coast.
          </p>
        </div>
      </header>

      <section class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="why-brevard-heading">
        <h2 id="why-brevard-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">
          Why Brevard County Is Different
        </h2>
        <p>
          High humidity, heavy rains, intense UV sun, and salt air near the coast cause paint to fail much faster here
          if the job isn't done right. Many homeowners end up repainting every 3–5 years instead of 7–10 because of
          poor prep or wrong products.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="what-changed-heading">
        <h2 id="what-changed-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">
          What Changed in 2021
        </h2>
        <p>
          In 2021, Florida eliminated the state licensing requirement for painting contractors. This means there is no
          longer an official state painting license to look for.
        </p>
        <p>
          While there are many good painters in Brevard County, homeowners now need to do a bit more vetting
          themselves — especially around insurance, communication, and clear expectations.
        </p>
      </section>

      <div class="watercolor-divider" aria-hidden="true"></div>

      <section class="space-y-8" aria-labelledby="look-for-heading">
        <h2 id="look-for-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">
          What to Look for Instead of a License
        </h2>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold sm:text-2xl">1. General Liability Insurance</h3>
          <p>
            This is an important protection for homeowners. It covers accidental damage to your house, windows,
            landscaping, or other property during the job.
          </p>
          <p>
            For most jobs, asking for proof of General Liability insurance is a reasonable step. For smaller or
            simpler projects, use your judgment — not every job requires the same level of verification. A reputable
            painter should be willing to show you their certificate without hesitation.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold sm:text-2xl">2. A Clear Written Agreement</h3>
          <p>
            You don't need a long legal contract, but it's smart to have the basics in writing before work starts.
          </p>
          <p>Most painters will provide a simple written proposal or estimate that includes:</p>
          <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
            <li>Which areas of the house are being painted</li>
            <li>The total price for the job</li>
            <li>Payment terms (deposit amount and when the final payment is due)</li>
          </ul>
          <aside class="rounded-xl border border-charcoal/10 bg-white/60 p-5 sm:p-6">
            <p class="text-base sm:text-lg">
              <span class="font-semibold text-charcoal">Tip:</span> If the job includes any uncommon or extra items
              (such as cabinet painting, specialty finishes, wallpaper removal, or extensive repairs), make sure those
              are clearly listed in the proposal. This helps prevent misunderstandings or surprise charges later.
            </p>
          </aside>
          <p>
            The most important thing is that you and the painter are on the same page about the price and what is (and
            isn't) included.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold sm:text-2xl">3. Experience With Florida Homes</h3>
          <p>
            Brevard County's weather — high humidity, intense sun, salt air near the coast, and frequent heavy rain — is
            very tough on paint. Painters who have worked locally for years usually understand which products hold up
            better and what preparation is needed so the paint doesn't fail early.
          </p>
          <p>
            <a
              href="/homeowner-guide/paint-products-florida"
              class="font-medium text-purple transition-colors hover:text-coral"
            >
              See our full guide to paint products and what holds up in Florida's climate →
            </a>
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold sm:text-2xl">4. Good Communication</h3>
          <p>
            You should feel comfortable with the person you're hiring. A good painter will clearly explain the process
            and keep you updated.
          </p>
          <p>Important things to know before the job starts:</p>
          <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
            <li>Who will be your main point of contact?</li>
            <li>How will they communicate (text, phone, email)?</li>
            <li>What happens if bad weather delays the schedule?</li>
            <li>Will they give you a realistic timeline for your project?</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Clear communication from the beginning usually leads to a much smoother painting experience.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="mistakes-heading">
        <h2 id="mistakes-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">
          Common Mistakes Homeowners Make
        </h2>
        <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
          <li>Choosing the lowest price without checking insurance or experience</li>
          <li>Not discussing prep work — ask what their process includes before you agree to anything</li>
          <li>
            Assuming all painters handle Florida's climate the same way — experience with local conditions matters
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="payment-heading">
        <h2 id="payment-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">Fair Payment Terms</h2>
        <p>
          A normal deposit for painting jobs in Brevard County is usually between 10% and 30%. The final payment is
          typically made after the job is complete and you're happy with the finished work.
        </p>
        <p>Never feel pressured to pay the full amount before the painting is done.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="estimates-heading">
        <h2 id="estimates-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">
          Practical Tips When Getting Estimates
        </h2>
        <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
          <li>Compare quotes</li>
          <li>Pay attention to how detailed the proposal is</li>
          <li>Watch how the painter talks about surface preparation and paint types</li>
          <li>Ask what they do to protect your home</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="lead-gen-heading">
        <h2 id="lead-gen-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">
          A Note on Lead Generation Platforms
        </h2>
        <p>
          Sites like HomeAdvisor and Angi are not vetting services — they're lead generation businesses. When you fill
          out a form, your contact information is sold to multiple contractors who pay for access to your inquiry. The
          responsibility for vetting is still entirely yours. Referrals from neighbors, direct Google searches with
          reviews, and companies with a verifiable local track record in Brevard County are more reliable starting
          points.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="checklist-heading">
        <h2 id="checklist-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">
          Quick Checklist Before Hiring
        </h2>
        <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
          <li>Proof of General Liability insurance (for jobs where it applies)</li>
          <li>A written proposal showing the price and what's included</li>
          <li>Good feeling about their communication and local experience</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          If something doesn't feel right or the painter gets defensive when answering basic questions, it's perfectly
          fine to keep looking.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section
        class="space-y-5 rounded-xl border border-purple/20 bg-purple/5 p-6 sm:p-8"
        aria-labelledby="project-cta-heading"
      >
        <h2 id="project-cta-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">
          Have a Project in Brevard County?
        </h2>
        <p>
          Feel free to reach out if you have questions or want to talk through your project. I'm happy to answer
          questions with no pressure and no obligation.
        </p>
        <p>
          <a href="/contact" class="font-semibold text-purple transition-colors hover:text-coral">
            Send a Message on the Contact Page →
          </a>
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted">
          Or call/text:{' '}
          <a href={phoneHref} class="font-medium text-purple transition-colors hover:text-coral">{phone}</a>
        </p>
      </section>

      <div class="watercolor-divider" aria-hidden="true"></div>

      <nav class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="more-guide-heading">
        <h2 id="more-guide-heading" class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">
          More from the Homeowner Guide
        </h2>
        <ul class="space-y-3">
          {moreGuideLinks.map((item) => (
            <li>
              <a
                href={item.href}
                class="font-medium text-purple transition-colors hover:text-coral"
              >
                {item.label} →
              </a>
            </li>
          ))}
          <li class="pt-2">
            <a href="/homeowner-guide" class="font-medium text-muted transition-colors hover:text-charcoal">
              ← Back to the Homeowner Guide
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </nav>
    </article>
  </main>
</Layout>
